#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:1
msgid "Start Date: 2014-07-16"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:2
msgid "RFC PR #: [\\#169](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/169)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:3
msgid "Rust Issue #: https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/16461"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:5
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:7
msgid ""
"Change the rebinding syntax from `use ID = PATH` to `use PATH as ID`, so "
"that paths all line up on the left side, and imported identifiers are all on "
"the right side.  Also modify `extern crate` syntax analogously, for "
"consistency."
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:12
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:14
msgid ""
"Currently, the view items at the start of a module look something like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:26
msgid ""
"This means that if you want to see what identifiers have been imported, your "
"eyes need to scan back and forth on both the left-hand side (immediately "
"beside the `use`) and the right-hand side (at the end of each line).  In "
"particular, note that `yummy` is _not_ in scope within the body of `old_code`"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:32
msgid ""
"This RFC proposes changing the grammar of Rust so that the example above "
"would look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:44
msgid ""
"There are two benefits we can see by comparing `mod old_code` and `mod "
"new_code`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:47
msgid ""
"As alluded to above, now all of the imported identifiers are on the right-"
"hand side of the block of view items."
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:50
msgid ""
"Additionally, the left-hand side looks much more regular, since one sees the "
"straight lines of `a::b::` characters all the way down, which makes the "
"_actual_ differences between the different paths more visually apparent."
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:55
msgid "Detailed design"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:57
msgid "Currently, the grammar for use statements is something like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:59
msgid ""
"```\n"
"  use_decl : \"pub\" ? \"use\" [ ident '=' path\n"
"                            | path_glob ] ;\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:64
msgid "Likewise, the grammar for extern crate declarations is something like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:66
msgid ""
"```\n"
"  extern_crate_decl : \"extern\" \"crate\" ident [ '(' link_attrs ')' ] ? "
"[ '=' string_lit ] ? ;\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:70
msgid ""
"This RFC proposes changing the grammar for use statements to something like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:72
msgid ""
"```\n"
"  use_decl : \"pub\" ? \"use\" [ path \"as\" ident\n"
"                            | path_glob ] ;\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:77
msgid "and the grammar for extern crate declarations to something like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:79
msgid ""
"```\n"
"  extern_crate_decl : \"extern\" \"crate\" [ string_lit \"as\" ] ? ident "
"[ '(' link_attrs ')' ] ? ;\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:83
msgid ""
"Both `use` and `pub use` forms are changed to use `path as ident` instead of "
"`ident = path`.  The form `use path as ident` has the same constraints and "
"meaning that `use ident = path` has today."
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:87
msgid ""
"Nothing about path globs is changed; the view items that use `ident = path` "
"are disjoint from the view items that use path globs, and that continues to "
"be the case under `path as ident`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:91
msgid ""
"The old syntaxes `\"use\" ident '=' path` and `\"extern\" \"crate\" ident "
"'=' string_lit` are removed (or at least deprecated)."
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:97
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:99
msgid ""
"`pub use export = import_path` may be preferred over `pub use import_path as "
"export` since people are used to seeing the name exported by a `pub` item on "
"the left-hand side of an `=` sign. (See \"Have distinct rebinding syntaxes "
"for `use` and `pub use`\" below.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:105
msgid ""
"The 'as' keyword is not currently used for any binding form in Rust. "
"Adopting this RFC would change that precedent. (See \"Change the signaling "
"token\" below.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:109
msgid "Alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:111
msgid "Keep things as they are"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:113
msgid ""
"This just has the drawbacks outlined in the motivation: the left-hand side "
"of the view items are less regular, and one needs to scan both the left- and "
"right-hand sides to see all the imported identifiers."
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:117
msgid "Change the signaling token"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:119
msgid ""
"Go ahead with switch, so imported identifier is on the left-hand side, but "
"use a different token than `as` to signal a rebinding."
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:122
msgid ""
"For example, we could use `@`, as an analogy with its use as a binding "
"operator in match expressions:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:133
msgid ""
"(I do not object to `path @ ident`, though I find it somehow more \"line-"
"noisy\" than `as` in this context.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:136
msgid "Or, we could use `=`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:146
msgid ""
"(I _do_ object to `path = ident`, since typically when `=` is used to bind, "
"the identifier being bound occurs on the left-hand side.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:149
msgid "Or, we could use `:`, by (weak) analogy with struct pattern syntax:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:158
msgid ""
"(I cannot figure out if this is genius or madness.  Probably madness, "
"especially if one is allowed to omit the whitespace around the `:`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:161
msgid "Have distinct rebinding syntaxes for `use` and `pub use`"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:163
msgid ""
"If people really like having `ident = path` for `pub use`, by the reasoning "
"presented above that people are used to seeing the name exported by a `pub` "
"item on the left-hand side of an `=` sign, then we could support that by "
"continuing to support `pub use ident = path`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:168
msgid ""
"If we were to go down that route, I would prefer to have distinct notions of "
"the exported name and imported name, so that:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:171
msgid ""
"`pub use a = foo::bar;` would actually _import_ `bar` (and `a` would just be "
"visible as an _export_), and then one could rebind for export and import "
"simultaneously, like so: `pub use exported_bar = foo::bar as imported_bar;`"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:176
msgid "But really, is `pub use foo::bar as a` all that bad?"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:178
msgid "Allow `extern crate ident as ident`"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:180
msgid "As written, this RFC allows for two variants of `extern_crate_decl`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:184
msgid "\"old_name\""
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:187
msgid ""
"These are just analogous to the current options that use `=` instead of `as`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:189
msgid ""
"However, the RFC comment dialogue suggested also allowing a renaming form "
"that does not use a string literal:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:196
msgid ""
"I have no opinion on whether this should be added or not.  Arguably this "
"choice is orthogonal to the goals of this RFC (since, if this is a good "
"idea, it could just as well be implemented with the `=` syntax). Perhaps it "
"should just be filed as a separate RFC on its own."
msgstr ""

#: src/0169-use-path-as-id.md:201
msgid "Unresolved questions"
msgstr ""

